INTRODUCTION

UK Electricity Consumption historical from 2009 -2024 data to forecast the demand for year 2025 using timeseries modelling

OBJECTIVE

The objective of the project is to analyze the historical electricity demand data and apply time series forecasting methods to predict the electricity demand for three output features i.e. NSD - National System Demand, TSD = Transmission System Demand and England and Wales region in 2025.

DATASET DETAILS

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/albertovidalrod/electricity-consumption-uk-20092022

Historic_demand_year_2009_2024.csv: all the yearly datasets merged in one

The columns in the dataset are:

Settlement_date: date in format dd/mm/yyyy Settlement_period: half hourly period for the historic period

ND (National Demand): It is the sum of metered generation, but excludes generation required to meet station load, pump storage pumping and interconnector exports. Measured in MW.

TSD (Transmission System Demand): It is equal to the ND plus the additional generation required to meet station load, pump storage pumping and interconnector exports. Measured in MW.

England and Wales Demand: As ND above but on an England and Wales basis. Measured in MW.

Embedded_Wind_Generation: This is an estimate of the GB wind generation from wind farms which do not have Transmission System metering installed. Measured in MW. italicized text

Embedded_Wind_Capacity: This is National Grid ESO’s best view of the installed embedded wind capacity in GB. Measured in MW

Embedded_Solar_generation: This is an estimate of the GB solar generation from PV panels. Measured in MW.

Embedded_Solar_Capacity: As embedded wind capacity above, but for solar generation. Measured in MW.

non_Bm_Stor: (Non-Balancing Mechanism SHort-Term Operating Reserve). For units that are not included in the ND generator definition. This can be in the form of generation or demand reduction. Measured in MW.

Pump_Storage_pumping The demand due to pumping at hydro pump storage units; the -ve signifies pumping load.

ifa_flow (IFA Interconnector Flow). The flow on on the respective interconnector. -ve signifies export power out from GB; +ve signifies import power into GB. Measured in MW.

ifa2_flow (IFA Interconnector Flow). The flow on the respective interconnector. -ve signifies export power out from GB; +ve signifies import power into GB. Measured in MW.

Moyle_flow (Moyle Interconnector FLow). The flow on the respective interconnector. -ve signifies export power out from GB; +ve signifies import power into GB. Measured in MW.

East_west_flow(East West Innterconnector FLow). The flow on the respective interconnector. -ve signifies export power out from GB; +ve signifies import power into GB. Measured in MW.

Nemo_flow (Nemo Interconnector FLow). The flow on the respective interconnector. -ve signifies export power out from GB; +ve signifies import power into GB. Measured in MW.

NSL_flow(North Sea Link Interconnector Flow). The flow on the respective interconnector. -ve signifies export power out from GB; +ve signifies import power into GB. Measured in MW. italicized text

# Function to partition data as data blocks for the given time period
def dataset(data,time_steps):
    x,y=[],[]
    for i in range(len(data)-time_steps):
        x.append(data[i:i+time_steps])
        y.append(data[i+time_steps])
    return np.array(x),np.array(y)

def model_fits(model,model_name,_lr_rate,epoch):
    optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=_lr_rate)
    cp4 = ModelCheckpoint('/tmp/ckpt/checkpoint.model.keras', save_best_only=True)
    early_stopping=tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='loss',patience=7,verbose=1,restore_best_weights='True',min_delta=0.0001,start_from_epoch=10)
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer,loss=tf.keras.losses.Huber(),metrics=['mse','mae'])
    history=model.fit(xtrain_combined,y=ytrain_combined,shuffle=False,batch_size=1, validation_data=(xval_combined, yval_combined),
                      epochs=epoch,callbacks=[early_stopping,cp4])
    print('')
    print(f"Model:{model_name}")
    print('')
    print('')

    #plotting the metrics of model- mse-mae and loss function is huber loss( a hybrid of mse and mae as it is regression)
    fig=plt.figure(figsize=(30,10))
    plt.subplot(131)
    plt.plot(history.history['mse'],color='Orange')
    plt.xticks(fontsize='20')
    plt.yticks(fontsize='20')
    plt.title(f'{model_name} - MSE')
    plt.subplot(132)
    plt.plot(history.history['mae'],color='turquoise')
    plt.xticks(fontsize='20')
    plt.yticks(fontsize='20')
    plt.title(f'{model_name} - MAE')
    plt.subplot(133)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'],color='purple')
    plt.xticks(fontsize='20')
    plt.yticks(fontsize='20')
    #plotting the loss performance of the model at training and test
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 4))
    ax.plot(range(1, len(history.history["loss"]) + 1),history.history["loss"],label="training loss",)
    ax.plot(range(1, len(history.history["loss"]) + 1),history.history["val_loss"],label="validation loss",)
    ax.set_xlabel("Epoch")
    ax.set_ylabel("Loss")
    ax.set_title("Loss evaluation")
    ax.legend(loc="best");
    return history,model

# Generate evaluation metrics
def metrics (Dataframe):
  metrics=pd.DataFrame()
  frame=Dataframe
  meansq=[]
  sqmeaner=[]
  mean_abs=[]
  mean_abs_p=[]
  for i,j in zip(('nd_ytest','tsd_ytest','ewd_ytest'),('nd_ypred','tsd_ypred','ewd_ypred')):
        meansq.append(mse(frame[i],frame[j]))
        sqmeaner.append(np.sqrt(mse(frame[i],frame[j])))
        mean_abs.append(mae(frame[i],frame[j]))
        mean_abs_p.append(mape(frame[i],frame[j]))
  metrics['Mean Squared Error']=meansq
  metrics['Squared Root (mse)']=sqmeaner
  metrics['Mean Absolute Error']=mean_abs
  metrics['Mean Absolute Percentage Error']=mean_abs_p
  l=['National Demand','Transmission System Demand','England and Wales Demand']
  metrics.index=l
  metrics=metrics.T.round()
  return metrics

Experiment 7 - Change the optimizer from Adam to SGD

In [ ]:
# learning rate schedule
import math
def step_decay(epoch):
        initial_lrate = 0.1
        drop = 0.5
        epochs_drop = 10.0
        lrate = initial_lrate * math.pow(drop, math.floor((1+epoch)/epochs_drop))
        return lrate
sgd = SGD(learning_rate=0.0, momentum=0.9)
# learning schedule callback
lrate = LearningRateScheduler(step_decay)
callbacks_list = [lrate]
early_stopping=tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='loss',patience=7,verbose=1,restore_best_weights='True',min_delta=0.0001,start_from_epoch=10)
# Fit the model

CONCLUSION

Based on the experiments conducted, here's an analysis of the strengths and limitations of your proposed solution, its implications, recommendations, feature importance, explainability, and deployment potential:

Overall Strengths of the Proposed Solution:

Time Series Approach: Using LSTM and other time series models is a relevant approach for forecasting electricity demand, as the data has a temporal component.

Data Preprocessing: The preprocessing steps, including converting to datetime objects, setting the index, grouping, scaling, and creating time steps, are appropriate for preparing the data for time series modeling.

Experimentation: You have conducted a variety of experiments by modifying the base LSTM model (changing epochs, learning rate, layers, dropouts, adding batch normalization, using CNN with LSTM, and trying bidirectional LSTM). This demonstrates an effort to find a better performing model. Evaluation Metrics: Using MSE, RMSE, MAE, and MAPE provides a good set of metrics to evaluate the performance of the models.

Limitations of the Proposed Solution:

Model Performance: While you have trained several models, the metrics from the base model evaluation indicate relatively high errors (MSE, RMSE, and MAE). This suggests that the current models might not be capturing the underlying patterns in the data effectively enough for accurate forecasting.

Limited Feature Engineering: The models primarily rely on past demand data. Incorporating external factors that influence electricity demand (e.g., weather data, economic indicators, holidays, time of day, day of week) could significantly improve forecasting accuracy.

Lack of Hyperparameter Tuning: While w experimented with learning rates, a more comprehensive hyperparameter tuning process (e.g., using grid search or random search) could lead to better model performance.

No Consideration of Long-Term Dependencies: While LSTMs are designed to handle sequences, the current time_steps=1 limits the model's ability to learn from longer-term dependencies and seasonal patterns in the data.

Implications of the Results for the Business Problem:

The current results suggest that the models, in their current state, may not be sufficiently accurate for reliable forecasting of UK electricity demand in 2025. The observed error rates indicate that the predictions might have significant deviations from actual demand, which could have implications for grid management, resource allocation, and planning for energy providers.

Data-Driven Recommendations for Solving the Initial Business Problem:

Enhanced Feature Engineering: Incorporate additional relevant features such as: Weather Data: Temperature, humidity, wind speed, and solar radiation are highly correlated with electricity demand. Calendar Features: Day of the week, week of the year, month, and year can capture seasonal patterns. Holiday Information: As you already have an is_holiday column, ensure it's effectively used in the model. Economic Indicators: Factors like GDP growth or industrial activity might influence demand.

Explore More Advanced Time Series Models: Consider other models better suited for complex time series data, such as: ARIMA or SARIMA: For capturing autocorrelation and seasonality. Prophet: A forecasting tool from Facebook designed for time series data with strong seasonality and trends. Transformer Networks: These have shown promise in capturing long-range dependencies in sequential data.

Hyperparameter Tuning: Implement a systematic approach to tune the hyperparameters of your chosen model (e.g., number of LSTM units, learning rate, dropout rate, batch size). Increase time_steps: Experiment with larger time_steps values to allow the model to learn from longer sequences of past data. Ensemble Modeling: Combine predictions from multiple models to potentially improve overall accuracy. Error Analysis: Analyze the periods where the model performs poorly to understand the underlying reasons and identify potential data or model improvements.

Most Informative Features of Your Model:

Based on your current model architecture (which primarily uses past demand data), the most informative features are the historical values of National System Demand (NSD), Transmission System Demand (TSD), and England and Wales Demand. However, as recommended above, incorporating external features is crucial for improving the informativeness of your model.

xplainability

Deep learning models like LSTMs are generally considered less explainable compared to simpler models like linear regression or ARIMA. Understanding the exact contribution of each input feature to the final prediction can be challenging. Techniques like LIME or SHAP could potentially be used to gain some insights into which input values are most influential for specific predictions, but full transparency is difficult to achieve.

Given the current performance metrics, deploying the model for critical real-time forecasting might be premature. It would be advisable to first implement the recommended improvements to enhance the model's accuracy and robustness. Once the model demonstrates satisfactory performance on a separate test set and meets the required accuracy thresholds for your business needs, then deployment can be considered. Deployment would involve setting up an inference pipeline to generate predictions in a production environment.

In summary, w have a good starting point with your time series analysis using LSTM. However, significant improvements in data, feature engineering, model architecture, and tuning are needed to achieve a reliable forecasting solution for UK electricity demand in 2025.
